'''Simon Wolf Oppenheimer''' (died 10 November 1726) was a [[Ashkenazi Jews|German Jewish]] banker and [[Court Jew]] of the [[Electorate of Brunswick-Lüneburg]] in [[Hanover]]. He was the son of [[Samuel Oppenheimer]], and was married to Frade Behrends, the granddaughter of [[Leffmann Behrends]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Stern |first=Selma |title=The Court Jew: A Contribution to the History of the Period of Absolutism in Europe |year=1950 |publisher=Transaction Publishers |page=213 }}</ref>
The astronomer [[Raphael Levi Hannover]] was a bookkeeper in his firm. His son [[Jacob Wolf Oppenheimer]] took over his banking business after his death in 1726, and later employed [[Mayer Amschel Rothschild]] as an apprentice between 1757 and 1763.<ref>{{cite book |last=Spingola |first=Deanna |title=The Ruling Elite: A Study in Imperialism, Genocide and Emancipation |publisher=Trafford |year=2011 |isbn=978-1-4269-5462-7 |pages=9–10 }}</ref>
