{{Germany-bio-stub}}

{{Distinguish |Żupan}}

'''Župan''' is a noble and administrative title used in several states in [[Central Europe|Central]] and [[Southeast Europe|Southeastern Europe]] between the 7th century and the 21st century. It was (and in [[Croatia]] still is) the leader of the administrative unit [[župa]] (or zhupa, [[županija]]). The term in turn was adopted by the [[Hungarians]] as ''[[ispán]]'' and spread further.

==Origin of the title==
The exact origin of the title is not definitively known and there have been several hypotheses: Slavic (F. Miklošič), Turkic-Avarian (A. Bruckner), Iranian (F. Altheim), Proto Indo-European (V. Machek), Indo-European (D. Dragojević), Illyrian-Thracian (K. Oštir), Old-Balkan (M. Budimir), among others.{{sfn|Peter Štih|1995|p=127}} The title was preserved primarily among the Slavic peoples and their neighbours who were under their influence.<ref name="Biliarsky">{{cite book |first=Ivan |last=Biliarsky |date=2011 |title=Word and Power in Mediaeval Bulgaria |url=https://books.google.hr/books?id=O-j66lYzINEC |publisher=Brill |pages=368 |isbn=9789004191457}}</ref> Its presence among [[Pannonian Avars]] and Avar language is completely undetermined.{{sfn|Peter Štih|1995|p=127}}{{sfn|Smiljanić|2007|p=34}} On the contrary of a specific theory, it should be noted that the title origin is not necessarily related to the origin of the titleholder.{{sfn|Peter Štih|1995|p=127}}

In 2009, A. Alemany considered that the title ''*ču(b)-pān'', often in a northeastern Iranian milleu, had an Eastern and Central Asian derivation, ''čupan'', and a Western and European derivation, ''župan''. The Eastern ''čupan'' first occurs, but allegedly as is usually connected with ''čupan'', in a [[Bactria]]n contract dated to 588 [[Anno Domini|AD]], where are mentioned two "headman" (''σωπανο'', "sopano");{{sfn|Alemany|2009|p=3}} among the [[Western Turkic Khaganate|Western Turks]] (582-657), the leader of the fifth Shunishi [[Uysyn|Dulu]] tribe was a ''chuban chuo'' (''čupan čor''), while the leader of the fifth Geshu [[Nushibi]] tribe was ''chuban sijin'' (''čupan irkin''), with ''chuo'' and ''sijin'' being the standard title of the each tribe's leader,<ref name="Golden">{{citation |author=Peter Benjamin Golden |author-link=Peter Benjamin Golden |title=Oq and Oğur~Oğuz* |publisher=Turkish and Middle Eastern Studies, Rutgers University |year=2012 |url=http://www.enu.kz/repository/repository2014/oq-and-ogur.pdf |pages=footnote 37}}</ref> inferior to ''qayan'' ([[khagan]]), but superior to ''[[Bey#Etymology|bäg]]''.{{sfn|Alemany|2009|p=3}} However, there is no mention of ''čupan'' in [[Old Turkic language|Old Turkic]] runic incsriptions;{{sfn|Alemany|2009|p=3-4}} a Chinese document (c. 8th century) near [[Kucha]] mentions severals persons (allegedly [[Tocharians]]) with patronymic Bai and title ''chuban'';{{sfn|Alemany|2009|p=4}} in the same century, in the Chinese documents of province [[Kingdom of Khotan|Khotan]] are mentioned word ''chiban'' and alleged title of low rank ''chaupam'';{{sfn|Alemany|2009|p=4}} the first (Old) Turkic document recording the title ''čupan'' is a [[Uyghur Khaganate|Uyghur]] decree from [[Turpan]] dated c. 9th-11th century.{{sfn|Alemany|2009|p=4}} According to the work ''Dīwānu l-Luġat al-Turk'' by the 11th century scholar [[Mahmud al-Kashgari]], a ''čupan'' is an assistant to a village headman.{{sfn|Alemany|2009|p=4}}

The first known mention of Western ''župan'' occurs in a charter of [[Kremsmünster]] abbey, by Bavarian duke [[Tassilo III, Duke of Bavaria|Tassilo III]] in 777 AD, in which the monastery was granted by a group of Slavs, headed by the chieftains Taliup and Sparuna, whose abode lied beneath the boundaries reported under oath by the ''iopan'' Physso;{{sfn|Alemany|2009|p=4-5}} the ''zo(ō)apan'' of [[Buyla inscription]] on a buckled bowl of a heterogeneous and chronologically uncertain (7th or 8th century) [[Treasure of Nagyszentmiklós]];{{sfn|Alemany|2009|p=5}} the ''supan'' in [[Sorbian languages|Lusatian]] and Latin language (7th century):{{sfn|Gluhak|1993|p=713}} the ''ζουπανος'' (zoupanos) on a silver bowl found at [[Preslav|Veliki Preslav]], capital of [[First Bulgarian Empire]] (893-972), and ''zhupan'' in Greek stone inscriptions and Cyrillic alphabet ([[Codex Suprasliensis]]) ;{{sfn|Alemany|2009|p=5}} the ''zuppanis'' in Latin charter of St. George's church at Putalj by Croatian duke [[Trpimir I of Croatia|Trpimir]] in 852 AD;{{sfn|Alemany|2009|p=6}} the Slavic, generally considered of [[White Croats]], title of king's deputy mentioned by [[Ahmad ibn Rustah|Ibn Rusta]] in the 10th century, the ''sūt.ğ'' or ''sūb.ğ'', of which corrupted text some transcribe as ''sūbanğ'' (probably Turkic ''[[Subaşi|sū beḫ]]'');{{sfn|Alemany|2009|p=6}} according to [[Constantine VII]] in his 10th century work ''[[De Administrando Imperio]]'', Croats, Serbs and other Slavic nations of Dalmatia had the ''ζουπάνους'' (zoupanous), "Princes, as they say, these nations had none, but only ''župans'', elders, as is the rule in the other Slavonic regions";{{sfn|Alemany|2009|p=6}} also the Croatian state was divided in 11 ''ζουπανίας'' (zoupanias) administrative regions,{{sfn|Alemany|2009|p=6}} with additional three ruled by ''βοάνος'' (boanos) or ''μπάνος'' (b/mpanos) ([[Ban (title)|Ban]]);{{sfn|Živković|2012|p=143}} and is individually mentioned ''ζουπανου'' (zoupanou) [[Beloje of Trebinje|Beloje]] of [[Travunija|Travunia]];{{sfn|Živković|2012|p=188}} later among Serbs it also temporary became a title for supreme leader '' ζουπανος μεγας'' (zoupanos megas, [[Grand Župan]]);{{sfn|Gluhak|1993|p=713}} in Czech sources ''supani'' (1187).{{sfn|Gluhak|1990|p=227}}

==Etymology==
In Polish, Czech, Slovak and Ukrainian allegedly from ''župan'' was shortened to ''pan'', meaning "master, mister, sir".<ref name=Kmietowicz>{{cite book |title=Ancient Slavs |author=Frank A. Kmietowicz |publisher=Worzalla Pub. Co. |year=1976 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=amTxAAAAMAAJ |page=185, footnote}}</ref><ref name="Oleg">{{cite web| url=http://www.v-stetsyuk.name/en/Scythian/Cimmer/SlavIr.html |title=To the Question of Slavic-Iranian Language Connections |author=[[Oleg Trubachyov]] |year=1965 |publisher=V.Stetsyuk |access-date=15 April 2015}}</ref>

*[[Franz Altheim]] derived the title from [[Iranian languages|Iranian]] etymon *''fsu-pāna''- that evolved to ''šuβān'' in [[Parthian language|Parthian]], ''šupān'' and ''šubān'' in [[Persian language|Persian]]; all these words meaning "shepherd".{{sfn|Alemany|2009|p=7}}{{sfn|Erdal|1988|p=227}} [[Gerhard Doerfer]] suggested possible Iranian origin for [[Mahmud al-Kashgari]]'s ''čupan'' linking it with New Persian ''čōpan'', a variant form of ''šubān'', with usual change of ''š-'' to ''č-''.{{sfn|Alemany|2009|p=7}} [[Omeljan Pritsak]] in Iranian *''fsu-pāna'' saw "shepherd of (human) cattle" in Avar service, using the Slavic masses as cannon fodder.{{sfn|Alemany|2009|p=7}} Some scholars derived it from alleged Old Iranian ''ašurpan/aszurpan'', meaning "great lord, noblemen".<ref name="Majorov">{{cite book |last=Majorov |first=Aleksandr Vjačeslavovič |year=2012 |title=Velika Hrvatska: etnogeneza i rana povijest Slavena prikarpatskoga područja |trans-title=Great Croatia: ethnogenesis and early history of Slavs in the Carpathian area |language=Croatian |location=Zagreb, Samobor |publisher=[[Brethren of the Croatian Dragon]], Meridijani |pages=95, 92–95 |isbn=978-953-6928-26-2}}</ref><ref name="Jerzy">{{cite book |last=Bechcicki |first=Jerzy |chapter=O Problematici Etnogeneze Bijele Hrvatske |trans-chapter=On the issue of ethno-genesis of the White Croatia |year=2006 |editor1-last=Nosić |editor1-first=Milan |title=Bijeli Hrvati I |trans-title=White Croats I |language=Croatian |location=Rijeka |publisher=Maveda |pages=8–9 |isbn=953-7029-04-2}}</ref> It is considered that the title origin can be traced to the [[Proto-Slavic borrowings#Slavic and Iranian|Slavic and Iranian]] cultural interrelation in the Eastern and Southeastern Europe in the first centuries AD.<ref name="Majorov"/><ref name="Jerzy"/>
*[[Karl Brugmann]] derived the [[Common Slavic]] *''županъ'' from ''župa'' "district, small administrative region",{{sfn|Brugmann|1900|p=111}} < ''*geupā'', comparing this word with [[Sanskrit|Skt.]] ''gopā-'' (herdsman, guardian), derived from ''gopaya'' (to guard, protect), of ''gup-'', or even ''go-pā'' (cow-herd), Avestan ''gufra-'' (deep, hidden), among others.{{sfn|Alemany|2009|p=7}} [[Oleg Trubachyov]] derived it from ''*gupana'' (from ''gopaya'', the guard of cattle).<ref name="Oleg"/> A Central Asian descent was claimed by [[Karl Heinrich Menges]], who considered ''župan'' a slavicized form of Altaic ''čupan'' (a loanword from Iranian), with modified meaning from "clan, community" to "district".{{sfn|Alemany|2009|p=8}} According to research done by scholars Ambroży Bogucki, Bohumil Vykypĕl and [[Georg Holzer]], in 2007 Franjo Smiljanić concluded that is excluded any Avar influence on the origin, yet within the Avar authority were preserved the remnants of Slavic tribal organization.{{sfn|Smiljanić|2007|p=34}}
*According to Alemany, the (Old) Turkic ''ču(b)'' is most probably a Turkic loanword from Khotanese ''-cū'' and Chinese ''zhou'' (perfecture), which was a Chinese territorial administration applied to Central Asian regions inhabited by Iranians, but it has even older meaning of small island; a township unit; a region, up to ''zhoumu'' (regional governor) from [[Han dynasty|Han]] to [[Sui dynasty|Sui]] dynasty.{{sfn|Alemany|2009|p=8-10}} Alemany pointed out that, as there were settlements of Central Asian Iranians at least in some of those ''zhou'', the title ''čupan'' as ''*ču(b)-pān'' (protecting a ''ču(b)'' or ''zhou''), was an Iranian rendering (see ''[[Marzban|marz-bān]]'', "protecting the marches"), of the Chinese ''zhoumu''.{{sfn|Alemany|2009|p=11}} The suffix ''-pān'' (from [[Avestan language|Avestan]] and [[Old Persian]] ''pat'', "protector"; ''pā-'', "to protect, to care") is well documented in [[Manichaeism|Manichean]] [[Parthia]]n texts from [[Turpan]], and lesser extent in [[Sogdia]]n and [[Kingdom of Khotan|Khotanese]].{{sfn|Alemany|2009|p=11}} He concluded that the title designs both ''regio'' and ''rector'', and if čupan was a loanword introduced by the Avars as some assumed, but there was already a common Slavic word ''župa'', their association could explain the shift ''č-'' > ''ž-'' in ''župan''.{{sfn|Alemany|2009|p=12}}

However, as the title among Avars is undetermined, on the basis of preserved toponyms which are etymologically related to the title župan, like ''Županovo kolo'' in [[Veliky Novgorod|Novgorod]], Russia, and ''Župany kolo'' in Ukraine, as well it was spread in Slavic languages which were not in contact with Avar language,{{sfn|Gluhak|1990|p=227}} the assumption it was of Avar origin is highly doubtful and dismissed by many scholars as it occurs in wider area than is the area where lived Slavs and Avars together.{{sfn|Smiljanić|2007|p=34}}{{sfn|Gluhak|1990|p=227}}

==Usage of the title and division==
The title had a widespread distribution, and did not always had a concrete institutional definition.<ref name="Biliarsky"/> Slavic tribes were divided into fraternities, each including a certain number of families.<ref name=ZU-Zupan>{{cite book|title=The Yugoslav village|author=Zagreb. Universitet. Institut za ekonomiku poljoprivrede i sociologiju sela. SOUR za sociologiju sela|publisher=Dept. of Rural Sociology|year=1972|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZQBPAQAAIAAJ|page=39}}</ref> The territory inhabited by a tribe was a ''župa'', and its leader was the ''župan''.<ref name=ZU-Zupan/>

The ''župans'', once as ''kopan'', of the First Bulgarian Empire are traditionally seen as Slavic chiefs,<ref>{{cite book |first=Kiril |last=Petkov |date=2008 |title=The Voices of Medieval Bulgaria, Seventh-Fifteenth Century: The Records of a Bygone Culture |url=https://books.google.hr/books?id=tjPEtxSOuYgC |publisher=Brill |pages=9–10, 37–38, 448, 508 |isbn=9789004168312}}</ref> or leaders of a local tribe and district.<ref>{{cite book |last=Curta |first=Florin |author-link=Florin Curta |date=2006 |title=Southeastern Europe in the Middle Ages, 500-1250 |url=https://books.google.hr/books?id=YIAYMNOOe0YC |publisher=Cambridge University Press |pages=164 |isbn=9780521815390}}</ref>
The ''župan'' title was also used in [[Wallachia]] and [[Moldavia]] (in modern Romania) but only with the meaning "mister" and bearing no administrative connotations.{{citation needed|date=March 2015}} 

===Croatia===
{{Main|Duchy of Croatia|Counties of Croatia}}

As heads of the ''županija'', the most important role of the ''župans'' were their public authority function.{{sfn|Smiljanić|2007|p=35}} They were the ''primates populi'', nobile aristocracy from where the king (or duke) recruited the official servants.{{sfn|Smiljanić|2007|p=36}} Those ''župans'' by origin most probably belonged to the tribal or noble family structure, in historiography known as "twelve tribes", which are mentioned in the [[Pacta conventa (Croatia)|Pacta conventa]] and [[Supetar Cartulary]].{{sfn|Smiljanić|2007|p=36}} In the Supetar Cartulary, and in Croatian redaction of [[Chronicle of the Priest of Duklja]], they were called as ''nobile sapienciroes'' and ''starac'' (elderman), indicating that to the agreement with king [[Coloman, King of Hungary|Coloman]] went twelve "elders župan".{{sfn|Smiljanić|2007|p=39}}

According to the charter by Croatian duke [[Muncimir of Croatia|Muncimir]] (892 AD) it can be identified various official functions; ''župans'' who work at the ducal palace (''Budimiro zuppani palatii'', ''Prisna maccererarii'', ''Pruade zuppano cauallario'', ''Zelestro zuppano camerario'', ''Zestededo zuppano pincernario'', ''Bolledrago zuppano carnicario'', ''Budimiro zuppano comitisse'', ''Augina zuppano armigeri''), who are part of territorial organization (''Zelllerico zuppano Cleoniae'', ''Sibidrago zuppano Clesae''), or are only noble by position (''Petro zuppano'', ''Pribritreco filius Petri zuppano'').{{sfn|Smiljanić|2007|p=35}} The ''župans'' were usually listed in historical documents only as witnesses, without mark of duty.{{sfn|Smiljanić|2007|p=35}}

The transition of 12th to the 13th century is characterized by  terminological change of the title ''župan'' and the spreading beyond the tribal main territory.<ref name="Damir">{{citation |last=Karbić |first=Damir |date=2004 |title=Šubići Bribirski do gubitka nasljedne banske časti (1322.) |trans-title=The Šubići of Bribir until the Loss of the Hereditary Position of the Croatian Ban (1322) |url=http://hrcak.srce.hr/index.php?show=clanak&id_clanak_jezik=11822&lang=en |journal=Zbornik Odsjeka za povijesne znanosti Zavoda za povijesne i društvene znanosti Hrvatske akademije znanosti i umjetnosti |publisher=[[Croatian Academy of Sciences and Arts]] |language=Croatian |volume=22 |pages=5 |format=PDF}}</ref> The older social rank of the ''župan'' (''iupanus'') in Latin documents was changed with the title ''[[Comes#Feudalism|comes]]''.<ref name="Damir"/> The Latin term ''comes'' in the 14th and 15th century Croatia was translated in two different ways, as ''špan'' and ''knez''.<ref name="Damir"/> The first signified the royal official in the ''županija'', while the second the hereditary lord of the ''županija'' exempted from the direct royal rule.<ref name="Damir"/> Thus the term lost its old tribal and got a new administrative meaning, while the old Croatian tribes (genus) under the title of ''knez'' preserved the inheritance rights over the lands of ''županija''.<ref name="Damir"/>

===Hungary===
{{Main|Ispán}}

There were several "ispán"'s in the royal court of [[Kingdom of Hungary|Hungarian Kingdom]]: 'nádorispán' ([[Palatine (Kingdom of Hungary)|palatine]]), 'udvarispán' (court ispán), 'kápolna ispán' (chapel ispán), and 'ispán's of the financial hierarchy ('harmincadispán', 'pénzverőispán', 'sókamaraispán', 'urburaispán'). Similarly the leaders of the ethnic groups were called 'ispán' like 'besenyők ispánja' ([[Besermian]] ispán) '[[Count of the Székelys|székelyispán]]' ([[Székelys|Szekler]] ispán).

===Serbia===
{{see also|Serbia in the Middle Ages}}

According to Fine, the governorship was hereditary, and the ''župan'' reported to the Serbian prince, whom they were obliged to aid in war.<ref>{{harvnb|Fine|1991|p=225}}</ref> The earlier ''župan'' title was abolished and replaced with the Greek-derived ''kefalija'' (''[[kephale (Byzantine Empire)|kephale]]'', "head, master").<ref name=Anderson290>[https://books.google.com/?id=sP_2-y9zKfgC&pg=PA290 p. 290]</ref>

===Slovakia===

The title ''župan'' is widely used as an informal name for presidents of self-governing regions (''župa'') in Slovakia.

